{"title_page": "Patreon", "text_new": "{{Short description|Crowdfunding platform}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name               = Patreon, Inc.\n| logo               = Patreon wordmark.svg\n| logo_size          = <!-- defaults to 250px -->\n| logo_caption       = <!-- or: | logocaption = -->\n| logo_alt           = \n| screenshot         = File:Patreon_screenshot_20_January_2018.jpg\n| screenshot_size    = <!-- default 300px -->\n| caption            = A Patreon page from January 20, 2018\n| screenshot_alt     = \n| collapsible        = yes\n| collapsetext       = Screenshot\n| location_city      = [[San Francisco]], [[California]]\n| location_country   = U.S.\n| url                = {{URL|patreon.com}}\n| commercial         = <!-- \"Yes\", \"No\" or leave blank -->\n| type               = [[Membership platform]]\n| registration       = Required\n| language           = English\n| num_users          = 3 Million monthly active patrons\n| content_license    = <!-- or: | content_licence = -->\n| owner              = <!-- or: | owners = -->\n| author             = {{unbulleted list|[[Jack Conte]]|Sam Yam}}\n| editor             = <!-- or: | editors = -->\n| launch_date        = {{start date and age|2013|5}}\n| key_people         = Jack Conte ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])\n| revenue            = \n| alexa              = {{Decrease}} 356 {{small|{{nowrap|(Global, {{as of|2019|10|01|alt=October 2019}})}}}} <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/patreon.com|title=patreon.com Competitive Analysis, Marketing Mix and Traffic - Alexa|website=www.alexa.com|access-date=2019-10-01}}</ref>\n| issn               = <!-- ISSN, e.g. 1085-6706 (automatically linked to http://www.WorldCat.org) -->\n| oclc               = <!-- OCLC number, useful where an ISSN has not been allocated (automatically linked to http://www.WorldCat.org) -->\n| current_status     = Active\n| footnotes          = \n| programming_language = \n}}\n\n'''Patreon''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|p|e\u026a|t|r|i|\u0252|n}}, {{IPAc-en|-|\u0259|n}}) is a [[membership platform]] based in the [[United States]] that provides business tools for creators to run a subscription content service. It allows creators and artists to earn a monthly income by providing exclusive rewards and perks to their subscribers, or \"patrons\".<ref name=\"PatreonHQ\">{{cite web | url=https://patreonhq.com/membership-is-the-future-for-creators-fc2902b8c16d | title=Membership: The Future for Creators | publisher=PatreonHQ | date=June 14, 2017 | access-date=June 14, 2017 | author=Conte, Jack}}</ref>\n\nPatreon is used by [[YouTube]] [[videographer]]s, [[webcomic]] artists, writers, podcasters, musicians, adult content creators,<ref>https://graphtreon.com/patreon-stats</ref> and other categories of creators who post regularly online.<ref name=\"New York Times\">{{cite news | url=https://nyti.ms/2nmEx8H | title=How The Internet Is Saving Culture, Not Killing It | publisher=NYTimes | date=March 15, 2017 | author=Manjoo, Farhad}}</ref> It allows artists to receive funding directly from their fans, or [[Patronage|patrons]], on a recurring basis or per work of art.<ref>[http://www.californiareport.org/archive/R201407111630/d The California Report.org:  \"Creating Patrons of the Arts Through Crowdfunding\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714225511/http://www.californiareport.org/archive/R201407111630/d |date=July 14, 2014 }} July 11\u201313, 2014.</ref> The company, started by musician [[Jack Conte]]<ref name=\"tri\">{{Triangulation|150|Jack Conte}}</ref> and developer Sam Yam<ref name=\"tri\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Olson |first1=Matthew |title=How Patreon Has Helped And Hindered Creators, As Told By 13 Users |url=https://digg.com/2019/patreon-creator-plans-user-interviews |date=May 7, 2019 |publisher=Digg |accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref> in 2013, is based in [[San Francisco]].<ref>[http://www.patreon.com Patreon.org: Intro] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301150012/http://www.patreon.com/ |date=March 1, 2014 }} Accessed July 14, 2014</ref>\n\nPatreon charges a commission of 5 to 12% of creators' monthly income, in addition to payment processing fees. Memberships are billed on the first of each month.<ref>{{cite web |title=Patreon - our fee structure |url=https://www.patreon.com/product/pricing/ |website=Patreon official website |publisher=Patreon |accessdate=August 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Patreon logo with wordmark.svg|thumb|250px|Logo used from May 2013\u2013June 2017]]\n\nPatreon was co-founded in May 2013 by Sam Yam and musician [[Jack Conte]],<ref name=\"tri\"/> who was looking for a way to make a living from his YouTube videos.<ref name=\"pbs\">{{cite news | url=https://www.pbs.org/mediashift/2013/09/donation-patron-services-help-fans-support-their-favorite-authors/ | title=Donation, Patron Services Help Fans Support Their Favorite Authors | publisher=PBS | date=September 9, 2013 | access-date=March 1, 2014 | author=Levitz, Dena | url-status=live | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413221932/http://www.pbs.org/mediashift/2013/09/donation-patron-services-help-fans-support-their-favorite-authors | archive-date=April 13, 2014 }}</ref> Together with Sam Yam he developed a platform that allows 'patrons' to pay a set amount of money every time an artist creates a work of art. The company raised $2.1 million in August 2013 from a group of [[venture capital]]ists and [[angel investor]]s.<ref name=\"wired\">{{cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/business/2013/10/big-idea-patreon/ |title=The Next Big Thing You Missed: 'Eternal Kickstarter' Reinvents Indie Art |publisher=Wired |date=October 22, 2013 |access-date=March 1, 2014 |author=Tate, Ryan |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227075539/http://www.wired.com/business/2013/10/big-idea-patreon |archive-date=February 27, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"time\">{{cite news | url=http://business.time.com/2013/12/04/business/slide/top-10-exciting-startups/ | title=Top 10 Exciting Startups | publisher=Time | date=December 4, 2013 | access-date=March 1, 2014 | author=Luckerson, Victor | url-status=live | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301040044/http://business.time.com/2013/12/04/business/slide/top-10-exciting-startups/ | archive-date=March 1, 2014 }}</ref> In June 2014, Patreon raised a further $15 million in a [[series A round]] led by [[Danny Rimer]] of [[Index Ventures]].<ref name=\"series A\">{{cite web | url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/06/23/patreon-raises-15-million-series-a-revamps-site-to-showcase-artist-content/ | title=Patreon Raises $15 Million Series A, Revamps Site To Focus More On Content | publisher=TechCrunch | date=June 23, 2014 | access-date=August 26, 2014 | author=Buhr, Sarah | url-status=live | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140825032045/http://techcrunch.com/2014/06/23/patreon-raises-15-million-series-a-revamps-site-to-showcase-artist-content/ | archive-date=August 25, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"$15M\">{{cite web|title=Patreon Raised $15 Million|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q5vAdw3WY9Q|publisher=YouTube|access-date=July 16, 2016|language=English|date=June 23, 2014|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004103952/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q5vAdw3WY9Q|archive-date=October 4, 2015 }}</ref> In January 2016, the company closed on a fresh round of $30 million in a [[series B round]], led by [[Joshua Kushner|Thrive Capital]], which put the total raised for Patreon at $47.1 million.<ref name=\"series B\">{{cite web | url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/01/19/patreon-gains-30-million-series-b-funding-experiencing-major-growth/ | title=Patreon Gains $30 Million Series B Funding To Support Growth | publisher=TechCrunch | date=January 19, 2016 | access-date=June 26, 2016 | author=Buhr, Sarah | url-status=live | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160531223037/http://techcrunch.com/2016/01/19/patreon-gains-30-million-series-b-funding-experiencing-major-growth/ | archive-date=May 31, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThey signed up more than 125,000 \"patrons\" in their first 18 months.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Amanda Palmer races to $13,000 per release in Patreon crowdfunding |date=March 4, 2015 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/mar/04/amanda-palmer-patreon-crowdfunding-backers|website = the Guardian|access-date = June 11, 2015|first = Stuart|last = Dredge|url-status = live|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150609094524/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/mar/04/amanda-palmer-patreon-crowdfunding-backers|archive-date = June 9, 2015 }}</ref> In late 2014, the website announced that patrons were sending over $1,000,000 per month to the site's content creators.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.patreon.com/creation?hid=1070951|title = Creators on Patreon Receive Over 1,000,000 per Month From Patrons|date = October 10, 2014|access-date = June 12, 2015|website = |publisher = |last = |first = |url-status = live|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150404133954/https://www.patreon.com/creation?hid=1070951|archive-date = April 4, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, Patreon acquired [[Green brothers#Subbable|Subbable]], a similar voluntary subscription service created by the [[Green brothers]], [[John Green (author)|John]] and [[Hank Green]], and brought over Subbable creators and contents, including [[CGP Grey]], [[Destin Sandlin]]'s ''Smarter Every Day'', and the Green brothers' own ''[[CrashCourse]]'' and ''[[SciShow]]'' channels.<ref>{{cite web|title=Patreon Acquires Subbable, Aligning the YouTube Stars|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alexpham/2015/03/16/patreon-acquires-subbable-aligning-youtube-stars/|website=Forbes|access-date=March 17, 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150319024318/http://www.forbes.com/sites/alexpham/2015/03/16/patreon-acquires-subbable-aligning-youtube-stars/|archive-date=March 19, 2015 }}</ref> The merger was consequent to an expected migration of payment systems with [[Amazon Payments]] that Subbable used.\n\nIn October 2015, the site was the target of a large [[cyber-attack]], with almost 15 gigabytes of password data, donation records, and source code taken and published. The breach exposed more than 2.3 million unique e-mail addresses and millions of private messages.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hunt|first1=Troy|title=Pwned websites - Patreon|url=https://haveibeenpwned.com/PwnedWebsites#Patreon|website=Have I been pwned?|access-date=October 7, 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151003211856/https://haveibeenpwned.com/PwnedWebsites#Patreon|archive-date=October 3, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Goodin|first1=Dan|title=Gigabytes of user data from hack of Patreon donations site dumped online|url=https://arstechnica.com/security/2015/10/gigabytes-of-user-data-from-hack-of-patreon-donations-site-dumped-online/|website=ars technica|access-date=October 7, 2015|date=October 2, 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151008042932/http://arstechnica.com/security/2015/10/gigabytes-of-user-data-from-hack-of-patreon-donations-site-dumped-online/|archive-date=October 8, 2015 }}</ref> Following the attack, some patrons received extortion emails demanding Bitcoin payments in exchange for the protection of their personal information.<ref name=\"BBC1\">{{cite web|title=Extortion attempt on victims of Patreon site hack|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-34899705|website=BBC|access-date=November 3, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104014114/http://www.bbc.com/news/technology-34899705|archive-date=November 4, 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"Billboard1\">{{cite web|title=Scammers Fumble Attempt to Extort Patreon Users|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/6770400/patreon-hack-extortion-attempt|website=Billboard|access-date=November 3, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161125040717/http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/6770400/patreon-hack-extortion-attempt|archive-date=November 25, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Techcrunch1\">{{cite web|last1=Biggs|first1=John|title=Extortionists Are Threatening To Release Patreon User Data|url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/11/21/extortionists-are-threatening-to-release-patreon-user-data/|website=Techcrunch|access-date=November 3, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104005652/https://techcrunch.com/2015/11/21/extortionists-are-threatening-to-release-patreon-user-data/|archive-date=November 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, Patreon sent out an email<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/patreon-paypal-adult-content|title=Patreon Ends Payments Discrimination Against Adult Content|last=Alptraum|first=Lux|date=July 27, 2016|work=Motherboard|access-date=December 13, 2017|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204090141/https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/patreon-paypal-adult-content|archive-date=February 4, 2017}}</ref> to its users, announcing changes for its more adult-oriented creators. Such content creators working under the \u201cNot Safe For Work\u201d (NSFW) categories on Patreon were now able to accept payments through PayPal via PayPal's subsidiary [[Braintree (company)|Braintree]]. This move now allows Adult Content creators on Patreon to accept payment more easily. Prior to this change, these creators could only accept payments through credit cards.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/10/27/patreon-adult-content-crowdfunding-uncertainty/|title=The real consequences of Patreon's adult content crackdown|work=Engadget|access-date=May 15, 2018|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180516103242/https://www.engadget.com/2017/10/27/patreon-adult-content-crowdfunding-uncertainty/|archive-date=May 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Patreon announced that it had sent over $100,000,000 to creators since its inception.<ref name=\"PatreonHQ.com\">{{cite web|title=Creators have made $100M on Patreon|url=https://patreonhq.com/creators-have-made-100m-on-patreon-ddfcc9338662|website=Medium|access-date=January 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, Patreon announced that it had over 50,000 active creators, 1 million monthly patrons, and was on track to send over $150 million to creators in 2017.<ref name=\"Techcrunch\">{{cite web|title=Patreon doubles in a year to 1M paying patrons and 50K creators|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/05/18/patreon-pushes-as-youtube-stutters/|website=Techcrunch|access-date=May 18, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518084819/https://techcrunch.com/2017/05/18/patreon-pushes-as-youtube-stutters/|archive-date=May 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Patreon announced a suite of tools for creators to run membership businesses on the Patreon platform. Notable improvements included a CRM system,{{clarify|date=August 2019}} a mobile app called Lens, and a service to set up exclusive livestreams.<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite web|title=Patreon Launches New Tools Following Forecast of $150M In Subscriber Funding|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7832871/patreon-launches-new-tools-following-forecast-of-150m-in-subscriber|website=Billboard|access-date=June 14, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170614170636/http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7832871/patreon-launches-new-tools-following-forecast-of-150m-in-subscriber|archive-date=June 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, Patreon announced the acquisition of Memberful, a membership services company.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/patreon-buys-memberful-as-tech-giants-compete/|title=Patreon Makes a Move as Tech Giants Encroach on Its Territory|work=WIRED|access-date=August 12, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Business model==\nPatreon users are grouped by content type, such as video/films, [[podcast]], [[comedy]], [[comics]], games, and education. These content creators set up a page on the Patreon website, where patrons can choose to pay a fixed amount to a creator on a monthly basis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patreon.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/203913859--How-do-I-become-a-creator-and-make-a-page-on-Patreon-|title=How do I become a creator and make a page on Patreon?|website=Types of questions|language=en-US|access-date=February 3, 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203163035/https://patreon.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/203913859--How-do-I-become-a-creator-and-make-a-page-on-Patreon-|archive-date=February 3, 2017}}</ref> Alternatively, content creators can configure their page so that patrons pay every time the artist releases a new piece of art. A creator typically displays a goal that the ongoing revenue will go towards, and can set a maximum limit of how much they receive per month. Patrons can cancel their payment at any time. Creators typically provide membership benefits (commonly in the form of exclusive content or behind-the-scenes work) for their patrons, depending on the amount that each patron pays.<ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1561353/jack-contes-patreon-anyone-can-be-a-patron-of-the-arts|title=Jack Conte's Patreon: Anyone Can Be a Patron of the Arts|work=Billboard Biz|date=May 10, 2013|accessdate=March 1, 2014|last=Pham|first=Alex|location=Los Angeles}}</ref><ref name=\"mercury\">{{cite news|url=http://www.portlandmercury.com/BlogtownPDX/archives/2014/02/07/portland-cartoonist-erika-moen-launches-a-patreon-also-patreon-sounds-pretty-brilliant|title=Portland Cartoonist Erika Moen Launches a Patreon (Also, Patreon Sounds Pretty Brilliant)|work=The Portland Mercury|date=February 7, 2014|accessdate=March 1, 2014|last=Henriksen|first=Erik|location=Portland, OR}}</ref>\n\nPatrons can unlock monetary tiers that increase the content type they see from the user. A number of content creators on Patreon are also YouTubers. They are able to create content on multiple platforms, and while the YouTube videos may be available to the public, the patrons receive private content made exclusively for them in exchange for aiding the Patreon user's goal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://smallbiztrends.com/2016/03/using-patreon-build-your-business.html|title=How Creative Entrepreneurs are Using Patreon to Build Their Businesses|website=smallbiztrends.com|language=en-US|access-date=February 3, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203162611/https://smallbiztrends.com/2016/03/using-patreon-build-your-business.html|archive-date=February 3, 2017}}</ref> Patreon takes a 5% [[Commission (remuneration)|commission]] on pledges. {{As of|May 2017}}, the average pledge per patron was around $12, and a new patron pledged to a creator every 5.5 seconds.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://patreonhq.com/what-patreons-growth-says-about-the-future-for-creators-9e3cc5e434dc|title=What Patreon's Growth Says about the Future for Creators|newspaper=Patreon|language=en|access-date=May 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|February 2014}}, almost half of the artists on Patreon produce YouTube videos, while most of the rest are writers, [[webcomic]]s artists, musicians, or [[podcast]]ers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patreon.com/discover|title=Explore Top Creators on Patreon - Patreon|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716000325/http://www.patreon.com/discover|archive-date=July 16, 2014}}</ref> {{As of|December 2016}}, Patreon's Community Guidelines allow nudity and suggestive imagery as long as they are clearly marked, but prohibit content that may be deemed pornographic or as glorifying [[sexual violence]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Community Guidelines|url=https://www.patreon.com/guidelines|website=Patreon|access-date=December 13, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161213201421/https://www.patreon.com/guidelines|archive-date=December 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nUnlike other online platforms such as [[YouTube]] and [[Facebook]], which use trained algorithms to identify potentially inappropriate content, Patreon's trust and safety team monitors users and investigates complaints of Terms of Service violations.<ref name=\"bowles\" />\n\n==Controversies==\nIn July 2017, conservative pundit and YouTube personality [[Lauren Southern]] was banned from Patreon over concerns about [[Les Identitaires|G\u00e9n\u00e9ration Identitaire]]'s blocking of [[NGO]] ships in the Mediterranean, ferrying migrants to Europe off the Libyan coast. A letter she received from Patreon said she was removed for \"raising funds in order to take part in activities that are likely to cause loss of life,\" referring to an incident in May involving Southern, and the larger [[Defend Europe]] mission in July, which she covered on YouTube. Philosopher, writer, and podcast host [[Sam Harris]], who also received contributions from patrons on the website, objected to Patreon's approach and announced that he would be leaving the platform because of it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/8/3/16084248/patreon-profile-jack-conte-crowdfunding-art-politics-culture|title=Inside Patreon, the economic engine of Internet culture|first=Adi|last=Robertson|publisher=The Verge|date=August 3, 2017|accessdate=August 5, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170804224805/https://www.theverge.com/2017/8/3/16084248/patreon-profile-jack-conte-crowdfunding-art-politics-culture|archive-date=August 4, 2017}}</ref> Shortly thereafter Patreon deleted the account of ''It's Going Down'', a [[left-wing]] news website, for allegedly [[doxing]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn October 2017, Patreon published an expanded version of its community guidelines, triggering a backlash from some adult content creators.<ref>{{cite web|last1=O'Donovan|first1=Caroline|title=Patreon Updated Its Rules On Adult Content, And NSFW Content Creators Are Worried|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/carolineodonovan/patreon-updated-its-rules-on-adult-content-and-nsfw-content|website=Buzzfeed|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028093901/https://www.buzzfeed.com/carolineodonovan/patreon-updated-its-rules-on-adult-content-and-nsfw-content|archive-date=October 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Kelion|first1=Leo|title=Porn-makers challenge Patreon's crowdfunding ban|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-41749885|website=BBC.co.uk|accessdate=October 28, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028014533/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-41749885|archive-date=October 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Cole|first1=Samantha|title=Adult Content Creators Are Fighting Patreon's New Anti-Porn Rules|url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/9kqye3/patreon-porn-adult-content-guidelines-open-letter|website=Vice.com|accessdate=October 28, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028094026/https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/9kqye3/patreon-porn-adult-content-guidelines-open-letter|archive-date=October 28, 2017}}</ref> A petition in protest at the changes gained 1,800 signatures, and drew a response from Jack Conte.<ref>{{cite web|title=An Open Letter to Patreon|url=http://www.openlettertopatreon.com/|accessdate=October 28, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027224015/http://www.openlettertopatreon.com/|archive-date=October 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Conte|first1=Jack|title=A Note to Our Adult Content Creators|url=https://patreonhq.com/a-note-to-our-adult-content-creators-abef831380e3|website=Patreon.com|accessdate=October 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Patreon announced a service fee starting on December 18, 2017, where some fees would be charged to the patrons rather than all fees being paid by the creator. This caused backlash from a number of creators, including some who saw members of their fanbase withdraw small pledges in response. Under the new payment model, a $1 pledge would have cost a patron $1.38, and a $5 pledge would have cost $5.50, representing a 38% and 10% rise respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2017/12/7/16747346/patreon-service-fee-pledge-creators|title=Patreon changes have creators concerned they'll lose income, supporters (update)|last=Alexander|first=Julia|date=December 7, 2017|website=Polygon|access-date=December 13, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171209100216/https://www.polygon.com/2017/12/7/16747346/patreon-service-fee-pledge-creators|archive-date=December 9, 2017}}</ref> Due to this backlash and the loss of many pledges for creators, Patreon announced that they would not be rolling out these changes, and apologized to their users.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.patreon.com/not-rolling-out-fees-change/|title=We messed up. We're sorry, and we're not rolling out the fees change.|last=Conte|first=Jack|date=December 13, 2017|website=Patreon|access-date=December 13, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213180550/https://blog.patreon.com/not-rolling-out-fees-change/|archive-date=December 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Patreon was accused of cracking down on ASMR ([[autonomous sensory meridian response]]) videos.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wilson |first1=Gaby |title=ASMR creators want you to know it's art, not a weird sexual fetish |url=https://news.vice.com/en_us/article/j5zam3/asmr-creators-want-you-to-know-its-art-not-a-weird-sexual-fetish |publisher=[[Vice News]] |accessdate=2 January 2019 |language=en |date=10 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Patreon banned far-right provocateur [[Milo Yiannopoulos]] a day after he created an account as well as far-right American political commentator [[James Allsup]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mastrine |first1=Julie |title=Prominent Patreon Creators Leave Site Over Political Bias. Should Big Tech Uphold Free Speech? |url=https://www.allsides.com/blog/prominent-patreon-creators-leave-site-over-political-bias-should-big-tech-uphold-free-speech |publisher=AllSides |accessdate=17 January 2019 |date=18 December 2018}}</ref> In the same month, Patreon also banned [[Carl Benjamin]] because he used homophobic and racist slurs in a YouTube interview in February 2018.<ref name=\"bowles\" /> Benjamin defended himself, claiming Patreon had taken his words out of context,<ref>{{cite web|title=You Cannot Trust Patreon|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4ThPdCicEsg&t=176s#|website=youtube.com|accessdate=December 29, 2018}}</ref> and that \"the video in question should not fall under Patreon\u2019s rules because it was on YouTube.\"<ref name=\"bowles\" />\n\nThis ban was criticized by Sam Harris and [[Libertarianism in the United States|American libertarians]], who have accused it of being politically motivated.<ref name=\"bowles\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/24/technology/patreon-hate-speech-bans.html|title=Patreon Bars Anti-Feminist for Racist Speech, Inciting Revolt|last1=Bowles|first1=Nellie|authorlink1=Nellie Bowles|date=December 24, 2018|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|accessdate=June 14, 2019}}</ref> Furthermore, [[Jordan Peterson]] announced a plan to launch an alternative service that will be safe from political interference, and jointly announced with [[Dave Rubin]] in a January 1, 2019, video that they will be leaving Patreon by January 15, 2019, as a direct response to its treatment of Carl Benjamin.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Goggin |first1=Benjamin |title=Top Patreon creators, of the 'Intellectual Dark Web,' say they're launching an alternate crowdfunding platform not 'susceptible to arbitrary censorship' |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/jordan-peterson-says-hell-launch-patreon-alternative-before-christmas-2018-12 |work=Business Insider |date=December 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Zp9ZJiFFBnU|title=We Are Leaving Patreon: Dave Rubin and Jordan Peterson Announcement|work=The Rubin Report|via=YouTube}}</ref> On January 15, Peterson and Rubin deleted their Patreon accounts.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.algemeiner.com/2019/04/24/how-much-did-youtube-and-paypal-make-from-owen-benjamins-jew-hatred/ |first=Dexter |last=Van Zile |date=April 24, 2019 |title=How Much Did YouTube and PayPal Make From Owen Benjamin's Jew-Hatred? }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Liberapay]]\n* [[OnlyFans]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|https://www.patreon.com/}}\n{{Sharing economy}}\n\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 2013]]\n[[Category:Companies based in San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2013]]\n[[Category:2013 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2013]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Crowdfunding platform}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name               = Patreon, Inc.\n| logo               = Patreon wordmark.svg\n| logo_size          = <!-- defaults to 250px -->\n| logo_caption       = <!-- or: | logocaption = -->\n| logo_alt           = \n| screenshot         = File:Patreon_screenshot_20_January_2018.jpg\n| screenshot_size    = <!-- default 300px -->\n| caption            = A Patreon page from January 20, 2018\n| screenshot_alt     = \n| collapsible        = yes\n| collapsetext       = Screenshot\n| location_city      = [[San Francisco]], [[California]]\n| location_country   = U.S.\n| url                = {{URL|patreon.com}}\n| commercial         = <!-- \"Yes\", \"No\" or leave blank -->\n| type               = Membership platform\n| registration       = Required\n| language           = English\n| num_users          = 3 Million monthly active patrons\n| content_license    = <!-- or: | content_licence = -->\n| owner              = <!-- or: | owners = -->\n| author             = {{unbulleted list|[[Jack Conte]]|Sam Yam}}\n| editor             = <!-- or: | editors = -->\n| launch_date        = {{start date and age|2013|5}}\n| key_people         = Jack Conte ([[Chief executive officer|CEO]])\n| revenue            = \n| alexa              = {{Decrease}} 356 {{small|{{nowrap|(Global, {{as of|2019|10|01|alt=October 2019}})}}}} <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/patreon.com|title=patreon.com Competitive Analysis, Marketing Mix and Traffic - Alexa|website=www.alexa.com|access-date=2019-10-01}}</ref>\n| issn               = <!-- ISSN, e.g. 1085-6706 (automatically linked to http://www.WorldCat.org) -->\n| oclc               = <!-- OCLC number, useful where an ISSN has not been allocated (automatically linked to http://www.WorldCat.org) -->\n| current_status     = Active\n| footnotes          = \n| programming_language = \n}}\n\n'''Patreon''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|p|e\u026a|t|r|i|\u0252|n}}, {{IPAc-en|-|\u0259|n}}) is a membership platform based in the [[United States]] that provides business tools for creators to run a subscription content service. It allows creators and artists to earn a monthly income by providing exclusive rewards and perks to their subscribers, or \"patrons\".<ref name=\"PatreonHQ\">{{cite web | url=https://patreonhq.com/membership-is-the-future-for-creators-fc2902b8c16d | title=Membership: The Future for Creators | publisher=PatreonHQ | date=June 14, 2017 | access-date=June 14, 2017 | author=Conte, Jack}}</ref>\n\nPatreon is used by [[YouTube]] [[videographer]]s, [[webcomic]] artists, writers, podcasters, musicians, adult content creators,<ref>https://graphtreon.com/patreon-stats</ref> and other categories of creators who post regularly online.<ref name=\"New York Times\">{{cite news | url=https://nyti.ms/2nmEx8H | title=How The Internet Is Saving Culture, Not Killing It | publisher=NYTimes | date=March 15, 2017 | author=Manjoo, Farhad}}</ref> It allows artists to receive funding directly from their fans, or [[Patronage|patrons]], on a recurring basis or per work of art.<ref>[http://www.californiareport.org/archive/R201407111630/d The California Report.org:  \"Creating Patrons of the Arts Through Crowdfunding\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714225511/http://www.californiareport.org/archive/R201407111630/d |date=July 14, 2014 }} July 11\u201313, 2014.</ref> The company, started by musician [[Jack Conte]]<ref name=\"tri\">{{Triangulation|150|Jack Conte}}</ref> and developer Sam Yam<ref name=\"tri\"/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Olson |first1=Matthew |title=How Patreon Has Helped And Hindered Creators, As Told By 13 Users |url=https://digg.com/2019/patreon-creator-plans-user-interviews |date=May 7, 2019 |publisher=Digg |accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref> in 2013, is based in [[San Francisco]].<ref>[http://www.patreon.com Patreon.org: Intro] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301150012/http://www.patreon.com/ |date=March 1, 2014 }} Accessed July 14, 2014</ref>\n\nPatreon charges a commission of 5 to 12% of creators' monthly income, in addition to payment processing fees. Memberships are billed on the first of each month.<ref>{{cite web |title=Patreon - our fee structure |url=https://www.patreon.com/product/pricing/ |website=Patreon official website |publisher=Patreon |accessdate=August 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Patreon logo with wordmark.svg|thumb|250px|Logo used from May 2013\u2013June 2017]]\n\nPatreon was co-founded in May 2013 by Sam Yam and musician [[Jack Conte]],<ref name=\"tri\"/> who was looking for a way to make a living from his YouTube videos.<ref name=\"pbs\">{{cite news | url=https://www.pbs.org/mediashift/2013/09/donation-patron-services-help-fans-support-their-favorite-authors/ | title=Donation, Patron Services Help Fans Support Their Favorite Authors | publisher=PBS | date=September 9, 2013 | access-date=March 1, 2014 | author=Levitz, Dena | url-status=live | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140413221932/http://www.pbs.org/mediashift/2013/09/donation-patron-services-help-fans-support-their-favorite-authors | archive-date=April 13, 2014 }}</ref> Together with Sam Yam he developed a platform that allows 'patrons' to pay a set amount of money every time an artist creates a work of art. The company raised $2.1 million in August 2013 from a group of [[venture capital]]ists and [[angel investor]]s.<ref name=\"wired\">{{cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/business/2013/10/big-idea-patreon/ |title=The Next Big Thing You Missed: 'Eternal Kickstarter' Reinvents Indie Art |publisher=Wired |date=October 22, 2013 |access-date=March 1, 2014 |author=Tate, Ryan |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140227075539/http://www.wired.com/business/2013/10/big-idea-patreon |archive-date=February 27, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"time\">{{cite news | url=http://business.time.com/2013/12/04/business/slide/top-10-exciting-startups/ | title=Top 10 Exciting Startups | publisher=Time | date=December 4, 2013 | access-date=March 1, 2014 | author=Luckerson, Victor | url-status=live | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140301040044/http://business.time.com/2013/12/04/business/slide/top-10-exciting-startups/ | archive-date=March 1, 2014 }}</ref> In June 2014, Patreon raised a further $15 million in a [[series A round]] led by [[Danny Rimer]] of [[Index Ventures]].<ref name=\"series A\">{{cite web | url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/06/23/patreon-raises-15-million-series-a-revamps-site-to-showcase-artist-content/ | title=Patreon Raises $15 Million Series A, Revamps Site To Focus More On Content | publisher=TechCrunch | date=June 23, 2014 | access-date=August 26, 2014 | author=Buhr, Sarah | url-status=live | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140825032045/http://techcrunch.com/2014/06/23/patreon-raises-15-million-series-a-revamps-site-to-showcase-artist-content/ | archive-date=August 25, 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"$15M\">{{cite web|title=Patreon Raised $15 Million|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q5vAdw3WY9Q|publisher=YouTube|access-date=July 16, 2016|language=English|date=June 23, 2014|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151004103952/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q5vAdw3WY9Q|archive-date=October 4, 2015 }}</ref> In January 2016, the company closed on a fresh round of $30 million in a [[series B round]], led by [[Joshua Kushner|Thrive Capital]], which put the total raised for Patreon at $47.1 million.<ref name=\"series B\">{{cite web | url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/01/19/patreon-gains-30-million-series-b-funding-experiencing-major-growth/ | title=Patreon Gains $30 Million Series B Funding To Support Growth | publisher=TechCrunch | date=January 19, 2016 | access-date=June 26, 2016 | author=Buhr, Sarah | url-status=live | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160531223037/http://techcrunch.com/2016/01/19/patreon-gains-30-million-series-b-funding-experiencing-major-growth/ | archive-date=May 31, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nThey signed up more than 125,000 \"patrons\" in their first 18 months.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Amanda Palmer races to $13,000 per release in Patreon crowdfunding |date=March 4, 2015 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/mar/04/amanda-palmer-patreon-crowdfunding-backers|website = the Guardian|access-date = June 11, 2015|first = Stuart|last = Dredge|url-status = live|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150609094524/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/mar/04/amanda-palmer-patreon-crowdfunding-backers|archive-date = June 9, 2015 }}</ref> In late 2014, the website announced that patrons were sending over $1,000,000 per month to the site's content creators.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.patreon.com/creation?hid=1070951|title = Creators on Patreon Receive Over 1,000,000 per Month From Patrons|date = October 10, 2014|access-date = June 12, 2015|website = |publisher = |last = |first = |url-status = live|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150404133954/https://www.patreon.com/creation?hid=1070951|archive-date = April 4, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, Patreon acquired [[Green brothers#Subbable|Subbable]], a similar voluntary subscription service created by the [[Green brothers]], [[John Green (author)|John]] and [[Hank Green]], and brought over Subbable creators and contents, including [[CGP Grey]], [[Destin Sandlin]]'s ''Smarter Every Day'', and the Green brothers' own ''[[CrashCourse]]'' and ''[[SciShow]]'' channels.<ref>{{cite web|title=Patreon Acquires Subbable, Aligning the YouTube Stars|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alexpham/2015/03/16/patreon-acquires-subbable-aligning-youtube-stars/|website=Forbes|access-date=March 17, 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150319024318/http://www.forbes.com/sites/alexpham/2015/03/16/patreon-acquires-subbable-aligning-youtube-stars/|archive-date=March 19, 2015 }}</ref> The merger was consequent to an expected migration of payment systems with [[Amazon Payments]] that Subbable used.\n\nIn October 2015, the site was the target of a large [[cyber-attack]], with almost 15 gigabytes of password data, donation records, and source code taken and published. The breach exposed more than 2.3 million unique e-mail addresses and millions of private messages.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hunt|first1=Troy|title=Pwned websites - Patreon|url=https://haveibeenpwned.com/PwnedWebsites#Patreon|website=Have I been pwned?|access-date=October 7, 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151003211856/https://haveibeenpwned.com/PwnedWebsites#Patreon|archive-date=October 3, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Goodin|first1=Dan|title=Gigabytes of user data from hack of Patreon donations site dumped online|url=https://arstechnica.com/security/2015/10/gigabytes-of-user-data-from-hack-of-patreon-donations-site-dumped-online/|website=ars technica|access-date=October 7, 2015|date=October 2, 2015|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151008042932/http://arstechnica.com/security/2015/10/gigabytes-of-user-data-from-hack-of-patreon-donations-site-dumped-online/|archive-date=October 8, 2015 }}</ref> Following the attack, some patrons received extortion emails demanding Bitcoin payments in exchange for the protection of their personal information.<ref name=\"BBC1\">{{cite web|title=Extortion attempt on victims of Patreon site hack|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-34899705|website=BBC|access-date=November 3, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104014114/http://www.bbc.com/news/technology-34899705|archive-date=November 4, 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"Billboard1\">{{cite web|title=Scammers Fumble Attempt to Extort Patreon Users|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/6770400/patreon-hack-extortion-attempt|website=Billboard|access-date=November 3, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161125040717/http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/6770400/patreon-hack-extortion-attempt|archive-date=November 25, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Techcrunch1\">{{cite web|last1=Biggs|first1=John|title=Extortionists Are Threatening To Release Patreon User Data|url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/11/21/extortionists-are-threatening-to-release-patreon-user-data/|website=Techcrunch|access-date=November 3, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104005652/https://techcrunch.com/2015/11/21/extortionists-are-threatening-to-release-patreon-user-data/|archive-date=November 4, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, Patreon sent out an email<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/patreon-paypal-adult-content|title=Patreon Ends Payments Discrimination Against Adult Content|last=Alptraum|first=Lux|date=July 27, 2016|work=Motherboard|access-date=December 13, 2017|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170204090141/https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/patreon-paypal-adult-content|archive-date=February 4, 2017}}</ref> to its users, announcing changes for its more adult-oriented creators. Such content creators working under the \u201cNot Safe For Work\u201d (NSFW) categories on Patreon were now able to accept payments through PayPal via PayPal's subsidiary [[Braintree (company)|Braintree]]. This move now allows Adult Content creators on Patreon to accept payment more easily. Prior to this change, these creators could only accept payments through credit cards.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/10/27/patreon-adult-content-crowdfunding-uncertainty/|title=The real consequences of Patreon's adult content crackdown|work=Engadget|access-date=May 15, 2018|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180516103242/https://www.engadget.com/2017/10/27/patreon-adult-content-crowdfunding-uncertainty/|archive-date=May 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Patreon announced that it had sent over $100,000,000 to creators since its inception.<ref name=\"PatreonHQ.com\">{{cite web|title=Creators have made $100M on Patreon|url=https://patreonhq.com/creators-have-made-100m-on-patreon-ddfcc9338662|website=Medium|access-date=January 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, Patreon announced that it had over 50,000 active creators, 1 million monthly patrons, and was on track to send over $150 million to creators in 2017.<ref name=\"Techcrunch\">{{cite web|title=Patreon doubles in a year to 1M paying patrons and 50K creators|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/05/18/patreon-pushes-as-youtube-stutters/|website=Techcrunch|access-date=May 18, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170518084819/https://techcrunch.com/2017/05/18/patreon-pushes-as-youtube-stutters/|archive-date=May 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, Patreon announced a suite of tools for creators to run membership businesses on the Patreon platform. Notable improvements included a CRM system,{{clarify|date=August 2019}} a mobile app called Lens, and a service to set up exclusive livestreams.<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite web|title=Patreon Launches New Tools Following Forecast of $150M In Subscriber Funding|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7832871/patreon-launches-new-tools-following-forecast-of-150m-in-subscriber|website=Billboard|access-date=June 14, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170614170636/http://www.billboard.com/articles/business/7832871/patreon-launches-new-tools-following-forecast-of-150m-in-subscriber|archive-date=June 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, Patreon announced the acquisition of Memberful, a membership services company.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/story/patreon-buys-memberful-as-tech-giants-compete/|title=Patreon Makes a Move as Tech Giants Encroach on Its Territory|work=WIRED|access-date=August 12, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Business model==\nPatreon users are grouped by content type, such as video/films, [[podcast]], [[comedy]], [[comics]], games, and education. These content creators set up a page on the Patreon website, where patrons can choose to pay a fixed amount to a creator on a monthly basis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patreon.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/203913859--How-do-I-become-a-creator-and-make-a-page-on-Patreon-|title=How do I become a creator and make a page on Patreon?|website=Types of questions|language=en-US|access-date=February 3, 2017|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203163035/https://patreon.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/articles/203913859--How-do-I-become-a-creator-and-make-a-page-on-Patreon-|archive-date=February 3, 2017}}</ref> Alternatively, content creators can configure their page so that patrons pay every time the artist releases a new piece of art. A creator typically displays a goal that the ongoing revenue will go towards, and can set a maximum limit of how much they receive per month. Patrons can cancel their payment at any time. Creators typically provide membership benefits (commonly in the form of exclusive content or behind-the-scenes work) for their patrons, depending on the amount that each patron pays.<ref name=\"billboard\">{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1561353/jack-contes-patreon-anyone-can-be-a-patron-of-the-arts|title=Jack Conte's Patreon: Anyone Can Be a Patron of the Arts|work=Billboard Biz|date=May 10, 2013|accessdate=March 1, 2014|last=Pham|first=Alex|location=Los Angeles}}</ref><ref name=\"mercury\">{{cite news|url=http://www.portlandmercury.com/BlogtownPDX/archives/2014/02/07/portland-cartoonist-erika-moen-launches-a-patreon-also-patreon-sounds-pretty-brilliant|title=Portland Cartoonist Erika Moen Launches a Patreon (Also, Patreon Sounds Pretty Brilliant)|work=The Portland Mercury|date=February 7, 2014|accessdate=March 1, 2014|last=Henriksen|first=Erik|location=Portland, OR}}</ref>\n\nPatrons can unlock monetary tiers that increase the content type they see from the user. A number of content creators on Patreon are also YouTubers. They are able to create content on multiple platforms, and while the YouTube videos may be available to the public, the patrons receive private content made exclusively for them in exchange for aiding the Patreon user's goal.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://smallbiztrends.com/2016/03/using-patreon-build-your-business.html|title=How Creative Entrepreneurs are Using Patreon to Build Their Businesses|website=smallbiztrends.com|language=en-US|access-date=February 3, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170203162611/https://smallbiztrends.com/2016/03/using-patreon-build-your-business.html|archive-date=February 3, 2017}}</ref> Patreon takes a 5% [[Commission (remuneration)|commission]] on pledges. {{As of|May 2017}}, the average pledge per patron was around $12, and a new patron pledged to a creator every 5.5 seconds.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://patreonhq.com/what-patreons-growth-says-about-the-future-for-creators-9e3cc5e434dc|title=What Patreon's Growth Says about the Future for Creators|newspaper=Patreon|language=en|access-date=May 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|February 2014}}, almost half of the artists on Patreon produce YouTube videos, while most of the rest are writers, [[webcomic]]s artists, musicians, or [[podcast]]ers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.patreon.com/discover|title=Explore Top Creators on Patreon - Patreon|publisher=|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716000325/http://www.patreon.com/discover|archive-date=July 16, 2014}}</ref> {{As of|December 2016}}, Patreon's Community Guidelines allow nudity and suggestive imagery as long as they are clearly marked, but prohibit content that may be deemed pornographic or as glorifying [[sexual violence]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Community Guidelines|url=https://www.patreon.com/guidelines|website=Patreon|access-date=December 13, 2016|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161213201421/https://www.patreon.com/guidelines|archive-date=December 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nUnlike other online platforms such as [[YouTube]] and [[Facebook]], which use trained algorithms to identify potentially inappropriate content, Patreon's trust and safety team monitors users and investigates complaints of Terms of Service violations.<ref name=\"bowles\" />\n\n==Controversies==\nIn July 2017, conservative pundit and YouTube personality [[Lauren Southern]] was banned from Patreon over concerns about [[Les Identitaires|G\u00e9n\u00e9ration Identitaire]]'s blocking of [[NGO]] ships in the Mediterranean, ferrying migrants to Europe off the Libyan coast. A letter she received from Patreon said she was removed for \"raising funds in order to take part in activities that are likely to cause loss of life,\" referring to an incident in May involving Southern, and the larger [[Defend Europe]] mission in July, which she covered on YouTube. Philosopher, writer, and podcast host [[Sam Harris]], who also received contributions from patrons on the website, objected to Patreon's approach and announced that he would be leaving the platform because of it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/8/3/16084248/patreon-profile-jack-conte-crowdfunding-art-politics-culture|title=Inside Patreon, the economic engine of Internet culture|first=Adi|last=Robertson|publisher=The Verge|date=August 3, 2017|accessdate=August 5, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170804224805/https://www.theverge.com/2017/8/3/16084248/patreon-profile-jack-conte-crowdfunding-art-politics-culture|archive-date=August 4, 2017}}</ref> Shortly thereafter Patreon deleted the account of ''It's Going Down'', a [[left-wing]] news website, for allegedly [[doxing]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn October 2017, Patreon published an expanded version of its community guidelines, triggering a backlash from some adult content creators.<ref>{{cite web|last1=O'Donovan|first1=Caroline|title=Patreon Updated Its Rules On Adult Content, And NSFW Content Creators Are Worried|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/carolineodonovan/patreon-updated-its-rules-on-adult-content-and-nsfw-content|website=Buzzfeed|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028093901/https://www.buzzfeed.com/carolineodonovan/patreon-updated-its-rules-on-adult-content-and-nsfw-content|archive-date=October 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Kelion|first1=Leo|title=Porn-makers challenge Patreon's crowdfunding ban|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-41749885|website=BBC.co.uk|accessdate=October 28, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028014533/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-41749885|archive-date=October 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Cole|first1=Samantha|title=Adult Content Creators Are Fighting Patreon's New Anti-Porn Rules|url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/9kqye3/patreon-porn-adult-content-guidelines-open-letter|website=Vice.com|accessdate=October 28, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171028094026/https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/9kqye3/patreon-porn-adult-content-guidelines-open-letter|archive-date=October 28, 2017}}</ref> A petition in protest at the changes gained 1,800 signatures, and drew a response from Jack Conte.<ref>{{cite web|title=An Open Letter to Patreon|url=http://www.openlettertopatreon.com/|accessdate=October 28, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027224015/http://www.openlettertopatreon.com/|archive-date=October 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Conte|first1=Jack|title=A Note to Our Adult Content Creators|url=https://patreonhq.com/a-note-to-our-adult-content-creators-abef831380e3|website=Patreon.com|accessdate=October 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, Patreon announced a service fee starting on December 18, 2017, where some fees would be charged to the patrons rather than all fees being paid by the creator. This caused backlash from a number of creators, including some who saw members of their fanbase withdraw small pledges in response. Under the new payment model, a $1 pledge would have cost a patron $1.38, and a $5 pledge would have cost $5.50, representing a 38% and 10% rise respectively.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2017/12/7/16747346/patreon-service-fee-pledge-creators|title=Patreon changes have creators concerned they'll lose income, supporters (update)|last=Alexander|first=Julia|date=December 7, 2017|website=Polygon|access-date=December 13, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171209100216/https://www.polygon.com/2017/12/7/16747346/patreon-service-fee-pledge-creators|archive-date=December 9, 2017}}</ref> Due to this backlash and the loss of many pledges for creators, Patreon announced that they would not be rolling out these changes, and apologized to their users.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.patreon.com/not-rolling-out-fees-change/|title=We messed up. We're sorry, and we're not rolling out the fees change.|last=Conte|first=Jack|date=December 13, 2017|website=Patreon|access-date=December 13, 2017|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171213180550/https://blog.patreon.com/not-rolling-out-fees-change/|archive-date=December 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Patreon was accused of cracking down on ASMR ([[autonomous sensory meridian response]]) videos.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wilson |first1=Gaby |title=ASMR creators want you to know it's art, not a weird sexual fetish |url=https://news.vice.com/en_us/article/j5zam3/asmr-creators-want-you-to-know-its-art-not-a-weird-sexual-fetish |publisher=[[Vice News]] |accessdate=2 January 2019 |language=en |date=10 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2018, Patreon banned far-right provocateur [[Milo Yiannopoulos]] a day after he created an account as well as far-right American political commentator [[James Allsup]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mastrine |first1=Julie |title=Prominent Patreon Creators Leave Site Over Political Bias. Should Big Tech Uphold Free Speech? |url=https://www.allsides.com/blog/prominent-patreon-creators-leave-site-over-political-bias-should-big-tech-uphold-free-speech |publisher=AllSides |accessdate=17 January 2019 |date=18 December 2018}}</ref> In the same month, Patreon also banned [[Carl Benjamin]] because he used homophobic and racist slurs in a YouTube interview in February 2018.<ref name=\"bowles\" /> Benjamin defended himself, claiming Patreon had taken his words out of context,<ref>{{cite web|title=You Cannot Trust Patreon|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4ThPdCicEsg&t=176s#|website=youtube.com|accessdate=December 29, 2018}}</ref> and that \"the video in question should not fall under Patreon\u2019s rules because it was on YouTube.\"<ref name=\"bowles\" />\n\nThis ban was criticized by Sam Harris and [[Libertarianism in the United States|American libertarians]], who have accused it of being politically motivated.<ref name=\"bowles\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/24/technology/patreon-hate-speech-bans.html|title=Patreon Bars Anti-Feminist for Racist Speech, Inciting Revolt|last1=Bowles|first1=Nellie|authorlink1=Nellie Bowles|date=December 24, 2018|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|accessdate=June 14, 2019}}</ref> Furthermore, [[Jordan Peterson]] announced a plan to launch an alternative service that will be safe from political interference, and jointly announced with [[Dave Rubin]] in a January 1, 2019, video that they will be leaving Patreon by January 15, 2019, as a direct response to its treatment of Carl Benjamin.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Goggin |first1=Benjamin |title=Top Patreon creators, of the 'Intellectual Dark Web,' say they're launching an alternate crowdfunding platform not 'susceptible to arbitrary censorship' |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/jordan-peterson-says-hell-launch-patreon-alternative-before-christmas-2018-12 |work=Business Insider |date=December 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Zp9ZJiFFBnU|title=We Are Leaving Patreon: Dave Rubin and Jordan Peterson Announcement|work=The Rubin Report|via=YouTube}}</ref> On January 15, Peterson and Rubin deleted their Patreon accounts.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.algemeiner.com/2019/04/24/how-much-did-youtube-and-paypal-make-from-owen-benjamins-jew-hatred/ |first=Dexter |last=Van Zile |date=April 24, 2019 |title=How Much Did YouTube and PayPal Make From Owen Benjamin's Jew-Hatred? }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Liberapay]]\n* [[OnlyFans]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|https://www.patreon.com/}}\n{{Sharing economy}}\n\n[[Category:Financial services companies established in 2013]]\n[[Category:Companies based in San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2013]]\n[[Category:2013 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2013]]\n", "name_user": "Palnatoke", "label": "safe", "comment": "link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patreon"}
